WEBVTT

00:00.160 --> 00:02.910
(dramatic music)

00:04.220 --> 00:06.840
- I'm visiting a historic
town in West Virginia

00:07.830 --> 00:10.040
where I meet one of
the most bizarre owners

00:10.040 --> 00:12.000
I've ever encountered.

00:12.000 --> 00:14.960
Just like Hoarders Anonymous,
junk on top of junk.

00:14.960 --> 00:17.350
Not only is she unaware of
the damage she has done...

00:17.350 --> 00:19.970
The wall's rotten, and you're
just gonna paint over it?

00:19.970 --> 00:20.803
- It's really solid.

00:20.803 --> 00:22.450
- You can't just Band-Aid this place.

00:22.450 --> 00:25.191
But her unwillingness to
change or even listen.

00:25.191 --> 00:26.670
(dramatic music)

00:26.670 --> 00:27.760
You're boiling a burger?

00:27.760 --> 00:28.810
- I eat them often.

00:28.810 --> 00:31.350
- We're all pretending that this is good.

00:31.350 --> 00:33.430
Proves to be the biggest hurdle for me.

00:33.430 --> 00:34.830
You are seriously in denial.

00:39.344 --> 00:41.927
(bright music)

00:50.060 --> 00:52.390
Just 60 miles from Washington, D.C.

00:52.390 --> 00:55.770
is one of America's most
celebrated small towns,

00:55.770 --> 00:56.763
Harpers Ferry.

01:00.080 --> 01:03.390
Situated between the beautiful
Potomac and Shenandoah rivers

01:03.390 --> 01:05.290
is the Town's Inn.

01:05.290 --> 01:09.730
- My wife Ana and I bought the
inn from my mom back in 2007.

01:09.730 --> 01:10.960
We want it to be a good investment,

01:10.960 --> 01:13.280
but we also bought it more
with our hearts than our heads.

01:13.280 --> 01:14.760
I think it's the type
of woman who's happiest

01:14.760 --> 01:15.593
when she's working,

01:15.593 --> 01:17.930
so we figured this would be
a good place for her to work

01:17.930 --> 01:21.430
and enjoy the season
of life that she's in.

01:21.430 --> 01:24.770
- I'm a grandmother, so it's
kind of "grandmother's house."

01:24.770 --> 01:28.830
And I'm here mainly because
I've retired from teaching.

01:28.830 --> 01:31.050
I love historical properties

01:31.050 --> 01:32.870
and decided that being an innkeeper

01:32.870 --> 01:35.120
would be a fun thing
for the rest of my life.

01:39.280 --> 01:42.360
- The Town's Inn is probably
kind of like a circus.

01:42.360 --> 01:43.610
Karan's the ringleader,

01:43.610 --> 01:45.830
and you never know
what's gonna happen next.

01:45.830 --> 01:49.830
- Working for Karan is
interesting, it's frustrating.

01:49.830 --> 01:52.040
She's pretty set in her ways.

01:52.040 --> 01:54.480
And it's her way or the highway.

01:54.480 --> 01:56.310
- I think what makes someone a good mom

01:56.310 --> 01:58.480
isn't necessarily what
makes someone a good boss

01:58.480 --> 01:59.700
or a good business owner.

01:59.700 --> 02:03.760
- Karan, as a businesswoman,
she don't have no experience.

02:03.760 --> 02:05.083
And that's awful.

02:08.520 --> 02:11.770
- Karan treats this place as
both her business and her home,

02:11.770 --> 02:14.000
but more her home.

02:14.000 --> 02:16.810
I mean, her bedroom is in her office.

02:16.810 --> 02:18.530
You know, she sleeps right there,

02:18.530 --> 02:20.760
pretty much in the dining room.

02:20.760 --> 02:23.150
- I have asked Karan, "Is this your home

02:23.150 --> 02:25.370
or a restaurant or is it a inn?"

02:25.370 --> 02:29.620
You can't have it all three
ways and expect to make money.

02:29.620 --> 02:31.730
- Karan is absolutely a hoarder.

02:31.730 --> 02:36.060
Karan hoards her clothes,
old shoes, books, baskets.

02:36.060 --> 02:38.890
- Don't even get me started
on those damn baskets.

02:38.890 --> 02:40.520
There's baskets everywhere.

02:40.520 --> 02:41.930
You could open a closet in the hotel room

02:41.930 --> 02:43.170
and could see a pile of baskets.

02:43.170 --> 02:45.110
You could walk in our server
area, open the fridge,

02:45.110 --> 02:46.610
and I bet there'd be a basket there,

02:46.610 --> 02:48.460
because they're literally everywhere.

02:52.320 --> 02:54.920
- Karan's in denial of what's wrong.

02:54.920 --> 02:57.470
She needs to separate
herself from this place,

02:57.470 --> 02:59.760
or things aren't gonna change.

02:59.760 --> 03:02.250
- We are suffering, we are in debt,

03:02.250 --> 03:04.490
and the customers are going away.

03:04.490 --> 03:06.460
- While we don't want
to sell the Town's Inn,

03:06.460 --> 03:09.027
I think we're certainly at
a crossroads of just saying,

03:09.027 --> 03:11.710
"Is this becoming
overwhelming for my mom?"

03:11.710 --> 03:13.420
You know, she's not getting any younger,

03:13.420 --> 03:15.670
and it just could be a
potential train wreck.

03:17.620 --> 03:20.470
So if the ship is sinking,
then we want to make sure

03:20.470 --> 03:23.403
we get our mom off of
the boat before it sinks.

03:26.510 --> 03:29.093
(bright music)

03:35.270 --> 03:37.183
- Wow, look at this place, gorgeous.

03:38.200 --> 03:39.953
Fresh food, wow.

03:41.060 --> 03:42.440
Nice to see you.
- I'm Karan Townsend.

03:42.440 --> 03:44.367
- Karan, good to see you.
- I'm glad you're here.

03:44.367 --> 03:45.740
- My, what a gorgeous little town.

03:45.740 --> 03:46.573
- Does it remind you of Europe?

03:46.573 --> 03:48.245
Isn't it kind of the quaint village?

03:48.245 --> 03:49.547
- It reminds me of a movie set.

03:49.547 --> 03:50.534
I mean, it's just literally--

03:50.534 --> 03:51.367
- It's been used as that many times.

03:51.367 --> 03:52.920
- Has it really, wow.
- Yeah.

03:52.920 --> 03:54.630
- [Gordon] Okay, let me just
have a quick look 'round,

03:54.630 --> 03:56.600
and, yeah, I'll follow you.
- Okay.

03:56.600 --> 03:59.150
- Um, what's all this
out here, what is that?

03:59.150 --> 04:00.650
Oh, that's just for watering the plants.

04:00.650 --> 04:02.490
- Yeah, and we get a lot of hikers.

04:02.490 --> 04:05.088
- Wow.
- And it rains here sometimes.

04:05.088 --> 04:06.138
- What is this?

04:06.138 --> 04:07.973
- Who knows? It's been here a long time.

04:07.973 --> 04:09.968
- It looks just like Freddy Krueger's hat.

04:09.968 --> 04:11.493
- It could be.
- Whose is this?

04:11.493 --> 04:13.493
- It's just there for anybody
that wants to borrow it.

04:13.493 --> 04:15.704
- Oh, I see. And does
anyone borrow that, Karan?

04:15.704 --> 04:17.089
No.
- They haven't yet.

04:17.089 --> 04:18.339
- Interesting.

04:18.339 --> 04:20.660
Another one as well and what, are these?

04:20.660 --> 04:22.810
- They're all for sale.
- Oh, they're for sale.

04:22.810 --> 04:24.990
- Yeah, see, summer hats.

04:24.990 --> 04:26.220
- How much are these?

04:26.220 --> 04:30.200
- Three to 20, depends.
- Three, and this is how much?

04:30.200 --> 04:31.560
- Uh, maybe not more.

04:31.560 --> 04:33.700
Whatever you want to
offer, we're very flexible.

04:33.700 --> 04:36.117
- I'm not too sure if it's my
style and that's dusty there.

04:36.117 --> 04:38.890
- That's a pretty special one.
- Why's it so special?

04:38.890 --> 04:40.630
Because it's got--
- Full of dust.

04:40.630 --> 04:41.902
- Yeah, West Virginia on it.

04:41.902 --> 04:43.600
- Uh, how much is--
- And this is almost heaven.

04:43.600 --> 04:44.580
- How much is that one?

04:44.580 --> 04:46.900
- It's whatever you offer.
- Are these second-hand?

04:46.900 --> 04:49.140
- No, not that, some
things are, but not that.

04:49.140 --> 04:51.070
- Well, it's your business,
are you selling many?

04:51.070 --> 04:52.200
Are you busy?

04:52.200 --> 04:54.070
- No, we don't really sell a lot of hats.

04:54.070 --> 04:55.650
- Oh, I see.
- Mm-hmm.

04:55.650 --> 04:57.270
- Well, you've got
customers in already. Hello.

04:57.270 --> 04:58.940
- This is my friend Sarah.

04:58.940 --> 05:00.390
- Sarah, oh.
- Nice to meet you.

05:00.390 --> 05:01.873
- Ah, well, good to see you.
- Nice to meet you.

05:01.873 --> 05:04.200
- Are you joining us for
lunch today, or are you--

05:04.200 --> 05:06.660
- I have no idea; I'm up to whatever.

05:06.660 --> 05:08.776
I'm here, I do-
- What does that mean?

05:08.776 --> 05:10.266
- She's just a family friend.
- Oh, you're a friend?

05:10.266 --> 05:11.836
Oh, okay, right, so you aren't
a customer, I'm so sorry.

05:11.836 --> 05:13.180
- I'm not a customer.

05:13.180 --> 05:15.250
- Is this a convenience store, or is it--

05:15.250 --> 05:16.550
- This is the dining room.

05:17.720 --> 05:19.643
- [Gordon] Wow, I mean, it's
very claustrophobic in here.

05:19.643 --> 05:20.476
- [Karan] It is.

05:20.476 --> 05:21.900
- There's bits and bobs of everything.

05:21.900 --> 05:23.680
Those freaky dolls, what are they for?

05:23.680 --> 05:26.530
- Well, they are sort of souvenirs.

05:26.530 --> 05:29.307
- Are you selling lots?
- We do, mm-hmm.

05:29.307 --> 05:30.330
- Wow, a bit dusty.

05:30.330 --> 05:32.270
- A lot of people who
come here have children.

05:32.270 --> 05:33.925
They're looking for
something to take back.

05:33.925 --> 05:35.570
- [Gordon] What about this
one here, collector's choice?

05:35.570 --> 05:37.910
How much is this one?
- I think $25.

05:37.910 --> 05:38.960
- Jesus, it's so dusty.

05:38.960 --> 05:40.203
- [Sarah] I didn't know
they were for sale.

05:40.203 --> 05:41.593
- [Gordon] You didn't
know they were for sale?

05:43.410 --> 05:45.100
How much does this room make a month?

05:45.100 --> 05:49.567
- Um... I can't give you
an exact figure because-

05:49.567 --> 05:50.400
- Right.

05:50.400 --> 05:52.420
- We record the purchases in
with the restaurant sales.

05:52.420 --> 05:53.253
- Yeah.

05:53.253 --> 05:55.250
- But I would say 15 percent of sales.

05:55.250 --> 05:56.920
- 15 percent?
- Mm-hmm.

05:56.920 --> 05:58.520
- Who drinks all this cider?

05:58.520 --> 06:00.740
- No, actually we use
that in the restaurant.

06:00.740 --> 06:01.660
- Jeez.

06:01.660 --> 06:02.767
- Well, but we sell a lot of it.

06:02.767 --> 06:06.143
It's good in the summer,
June, July, and August.

06:07.120 --> 06:09.540
Now, my daughter made those.
- Right, what are they?

06:09.540 --> 06:11.050
- They're little hats for little children.

06:11.050 --> 06:12.490
- It's full of dust and hair.

06:12.490 --> 06:13.770
And what's this?

06:13.770 --> 06:15.370
- [Karan] Hot pads, hand-made.

06:15.370 --> 06:16.203
- Hot pads?
- Mm-hmm.

06:16.203 --> 06:18.170
- Is that $60?

06:18.170 --> 06:19.260
Who buys this?

06:19.260 --> 06:20.830
- People with children.

06:20.830 --> 06:22.330
- I hope people with children.

06:23.910 --> 06:25.490
That's full of dust inside.

06:25.490 --> 06:27.940
- Well, you have to wash
it before you use it.

06:27.940 --> 06:28.773
- Look.

06:32.470 --> 06:34.930
And what's this, uh--
- This is Sarah's journal.

06:34.930 --> 06:36.490
- So she keeps a journal?
- Yeah.

06:36.490 --> 06:39.681
- Wow, so it's almost like a novel.

06:39.681 --> 06:41.540
- It is, and she puts sermon notes

06:41.540 --> 06:43.202
and telephone numbers, and prices--

06:43.202 --> 06:45.330
- Wow.
- She calls it her brain.

06:45.330 --> 06:47.890
- Look: public bathroom,
decorate with baskets, wow.

06:47.890 --> 06:51.008
- Yeah. She decorated the
baskets up in my washroom.

06:51.008 --> 06:53.040
- Oh, Oh, dear.

06:53.040 --> 06:55.260
Okay, wow, so, um--

06:55.260 --> 06:56.543
- All right.
- What's that there?

06:56.543 --> 06:58.110
- That is a bottle holder.

06:58.110 --> 06:59.657
You can put like a water bottle in it.

06:59.657 --> 07:01.060
- Oh.
- So it does appeal to--

07:01.060 --> 07:02.834
- Wow, I thought it was a
jock strap. Do you know what--

07:02.834 --> 07:05.570
- Uh, you know, it could-
- It looks like a jock strap.

07:05.570 --> 07:06.467
- I hadn't thought of that--
- Wow.

07:06.467 --> 07:08.357
- But you got a point.

07:08.357 --> 07:10.460
- What's that down there?
- This, that's our bread.

07:10.460 --> 07:12.960
And then behind that is the closet

07:12.960 --> 07:14.720
where our potatoes are kept.

07:14.720 --> 07:17.063
- But are, are the loaves for sale too?

07:18.090 --> 07:20.790
- If someone asks for them,
and hikers do sometime,

07:20.790 --> 07:23.950
but normally it's just for the breakfast.

07:23.950 --> 07:24.783
We have toast.

07:24.783 --> 07:26.030
- You expecting a lot of people?

07:26.030 --> 07:27.750
- That's how much we go
through in a few days,

07:27.750 --> 07:28.666
believe it or not.

07:28.666 --> 07:29.499
- Really?

07:29.499 --> 07:31.070
Unfortunately, they're
out of date as well.

07:31.070 --> 07:32.570
- Couldn't, are you serious?

07:32.570 --> 07:34.250
- 2nd of November.

07:34.250 --> 07:36.440
- Okay, you're right, today's the 6th.

07:36.440 --> 07:37.600
Oh, that's very embarrassing.

07:37.600 --> 07:39.593
- Damn, let's go to my room.

07:41.730 --> 07:42.760
What is that?

07:42.760 --> 07:44.073
- Oh, these are my famous baskets.

07:44.073 --> 07:44.906
- Baskets? Jesus.

07:44.906 --> 07:46.750
- Yeah, I love baskets,
and I collect them.

07:46.750 --> 07:47.890
- Beautiful Baskets 4 Sale.

07:47.890 --> 07:49.820
Prices vary from $1 to $30.

07:49.820 --> 07:51.307
Stop it. $30?

07:51.307 --> 07:52.800
- Well-
- Man!

07:52.800 --> 07:54.640
- [Karan] Some of them are very unique.

07:54.640 --> 07:56.657
- You're telling me that
families come in here

07:56.657 --> 07:58.870
and they go for a hike,
and they buy these baskets

07:58.870 --> 08:00.130
on the way?
- Mm-hmm.

08:00.130 --> 08:01.640
- To the mountains?
- Mm-hmm.

08:01.640 --> 08:03.290
- Stop.

08:03.290 --> 08:04.650
This one's full of bugs.

08:04.650 --> 08:06.167
- [Karan] I guess I wouldn't
buy that one, would you?

08:06.167 --> 08:07.690
- $12?
- Mm-hmm.

08:07.690 --> 08:08.880
- And that's with the cockroaches?

08:08.880 --> 08:10.480
- [Karan] We don't charge extra.

08:11.390 --> 08:13.740
- Wow, that was 12.99,
it's reduced down to $5.

08:14.640 --> 08:16.663
Oh, bugs in there, as well, bloody hell.

08:17.949 --> 08:20.150
Do you get them as gifts
and then resell them?

08:20.150 --> 08:22.686
- No, I just buy them
when I find them places.

08:22.686 --> 08:24.755
I collect them.
- Oh, what the hell is that?

08:24.755 --> 08:27.330
- It's a Easter basket.
- Ah, that's an Easter basket?

08:27.330 --> 08:28.750
Fucking hell, poor bunny.

08:28.750 --> 08:30.493
And how much is that, $1.

08:30.493 --> 08:33.020
- Yep.
- Wow, can you go any lower?

08:33.020 --> 08:34.049
- Nope.
- Eh?

08:34.049 --> 08:35.929
- We don't deal in cents.

08:35.929 --> 08:39.070
- Ay, yi, yi. Karan, you're
starting to scare me.

08:39.070 --> 08:40.823
Seriously, you are a basket case.

08:40.823 --> 08:41.657
- That's a good point.

08:41.657 --> 08:44.950
- Honestly, there's dust
everywhere up here as well.

08:44.950 --> 08:47.080
When was the last time
this place was dusted?

08:47.080 --> 08:48.660
- Uh, theoretically, every day.

08:48.660 --> 08:50.210
- Every, oh, every day?
- Yeah.

08:50.210 --> 08:52.150
- This is my room named after-
- This is.

08:52.150 --> 08:53.650
- The river.
- Potomac River.

08:55.090 --> 08:56.883
- Wow. Bloody hell.

08:58.288 --> 08:59.563
Oh, dear, and this is it?

09:00.420 --> 09:03.390
Wow, uh... wow.

09:03.390 --> 09:06.700
- We have five rooms, this one is 130.

09:06.700 --> 09:08.143
- Oh! Oh, shit.

09:10.912 --> 09:12.520
What happened there?

09:12.520 --> 09:13.570
- You're taller than I am.

09:13.570 --> 09:16.740
See, it just lays up there on top of the,

09:16.740 --> 09:18.150
no, see, there you go.

09:18.150 --> 09:20.660
- [Gordon] The pole is too
short, my darling, look.

09:20.660 --> 09:23.110
So, you see?
- There you go.

09:23.980 --> 09:26.048
- [Gordon] Look, that's there.

09:26.048 --> 09:28.270
- And this has been here since 2007-

09:28.270 --> 09:30.410
- Right.
- And it's never fallen down.

09:30.410 --> 09:31.493
- Oh, really?

09:32.790 --> 09:34.663
Flippin' A, oh shit.
(tin clattering)

09:34.663 --> 09:35.496
- [Karan] Okay.

09:35.496 --> 09:36.329
- Let's leave them there for now

09:36.329 --> 09:37.500
and let's get some light in here.

09:37.500 --> 09:41.371
Okay, I'm gonna unpack and-
- That, that's private.

09:41.371 --> 09:43.230
- What do you mean, it's
private, this is my bedroom.

09:43.230 --> 09:45.630
- Uh, well, but this is off-limits.

09:45.630 --> 09:48.253
It's got a lock on it,
it's like a storage closet.

09:49.190 --> 09:50.730
- But if I'm paying for the room

09:50.730 --> 09:52.130
I'd like to get into my wardrobe.

09:52.130 --> 09:53.050
- You're not paying for that,

09:53.050 --> 09:54.950
you're paying for everything else.

09:54.950 --> 09:56.420
- Well, then.

09:56.420 --> 09:57.253
- We've got these little things

09:57.253 --> 09:59.030
you can put your suitcase on.

09:59.030 --> 10:00.330
- But what's in here?

10:00.330 --> 10:01.770
- My clothes.

10:01.770 --> 10:04.000
- Your clothes?
- Mm-hmm.

10:04.000 --> 10:04.833
- Seriously?

10:04.833 --> 10:05.666
- Seriously.
- So you-

10:05.666 --> 10:07.397
- And it's very inconvenient
when there are people here

10:07.397 --> 10:10.700
and I can't get to my
clothes, but I live with it.

10:10.700 --> 10:13.661
- Um, I want to hang my
clothes in my wardrobe.

10:13.661 --> 10:16.520
- 1840, we use hooks.

10:16.520 --> 10:18.100
- Hooks.
- Mm-hmm.

10:18.100 --> 10:20.470
- Uh, why don't you get
me the key to open this?

10:20.470 --> 10:22.595
I need to hang my, uh, my jacket.

10:22.595 --> 10:24.845
- [Karan] Uh, you'll
just have to use a hook.

10:26.050 --> 10:27.960
- Um, once again, this is a rental.

10:27.960 --> 10:29.410
You're renting me a room.

10:29.410 --> 10:32.290
I'm here to help you, and
I'd like to use my wardrobe.

10:32.290 --> 10:33.561
- Mm-hmm.

10:33.561 --> 10:35.060
- Could I have a look inside then, please,

10:35.060 --> 10:37.593
'cause I'm just worried in
case you put somebody in there.

10:40.920 --> 10:42.720
- [Karan] There you go.

10:42.720 --> 10:46.593
- There are all your clothes?
- Mm-hmm, literally all.

10:46.593 --> 10:48.270
- That's it?
- That's it.

10:48.270 --> 10:51.580
Well, there's a few jackets
in the wardrobe upstairs.

10:51.580 --> 10:52.825
- So you have another wardrobe?

10:52.825 --> 10:54.260
- Right above us is another room.

10:54.260 --> 10:55.830
- And another room that you rent out...

10:55.830 --> 10:57.530
- With a padlock on.
- Mm-hmm.

10:57.530 --> 10:59.400
- Come on, you're paying $130

10:59.400 --> 11:01.230
for the owner's clothes
to stay in the wardrobe.

11:01.230 --> 11:03.080
That's a first for me, congratulations.

11:03.080 --> 11:04.010
I feel really uncomfortable

11:04.010 --> 11:07.033
about having my wardrobe
full of all your clothes.

11:08.160 --> 11:09.160
- I can cover it up,

11:09.160 --> 11:11.330
but it stays locked, so
you can just ignore it.

11:11.330 --> 11:14.160
- Can I just have half of
this, then? Do you mind?

11:14.160 --> 11:15.540
- [Karan] Oh, okay.

11:15.540 --> 11:17.150
Chelle?

11:17.150 --> 11:17.983
Chelle?

11:22.540 --> 11:27.340
- Wow, how much shit can
one get into the wardrobe?

11:27.340 --> 11:29.270
